+
+## CVE-2026-4438 — Not applicable on glibc 2.35 (Ubuntu Jammy)
+
+### Overview
+
+CVE-2026-4438 affects reverse DNS lookups via `gethostbyaddr`. In affected glibc versions, `getanswer_ptr()` validated `expected_name` (the query name) with `__res_binary_hnok()` instead of `name_buffer` (the unpacked PTR target). A malicious DNS server could return hostnames with shell metacharacters that bypass the check.
+
+**Upstream fix:** commit `e109774` — validate `name_buffer` instead of `expected_name` ([BZ #34015](https://sourceware.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=34015)).
+
+### Why Jammy does not need this patch
+
+| Item | Jammy (2.35) | Affected releases (2.37+) |
+|------|--------------|---------------------------|
+| Function | `getanswer_r()` | `getanswer_ptr()` |
+| PTR hostname check | `__libc_res_hnok (bp)` on unpacked response | `__res_binary_hnok (expected_name)` (buggy) |
+| Introduced in | glibc 2.35 base | glibc 2.37 resolver refactor |
+
+Ubuntu Jammy ships glibc **2.35-0ubuntu3.x**. The buggy `getanswer_ptr()` function **does not exist** in this tree. The upstream patch hunks fail to apply.
+
+Jammy's PTR handling in `getanswer_r()` validates the unpacked response hostname after `__ns_name_ntop`, not the reverse-lookup query name.
+
+### Verdict
+
+**No code patch required** — not applicable to glibc 2.35. Scanners may flag this CVE on Jammy due to broad NVD version ranges; the vulnerable code path exists only from glibc 2.37.
+
+### References
+
+- [NVD – CVE-2026-4438](https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2026-4438)
+- [Sourceware BZ #34015](https://sourceware.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=34015)
+- [Upstream fix – e109774](https://sourceware.org/git/?p=glibc.git;a=commit;h=e10977481f4db4b2a3ce34fa4c3a1e26651ae312)
+<!-- SECURITY-RELEASE-ANCHOR -->
